            "author_info": {
                "name": "Ernest W. Adams",
                "href": "/profile/Ernest-W-Adams"
            },
            "answer_text": "It depends on exactly how and why they change their borders. In the past, some states have ceded land to the federal government, and that land became a territory of the United States and not part of a state. Congress determines the boundaries of states as of the time they enter the Union, and can create new states (Kentucky and West Virginia from Virginia, for example). To change a boundary between two existing states, state governments of the two states would have to both agree, probably by each passing suitable legislation, and then ask Congress to make it official. Sometimes there are disputes between two states when they both claim the same land. This is occasionally settled by Congress or by the Supreme Court. The case New Jersey v. New York determined that 90% of the famous Ellis Island, where immigrants were processed, actually belongs to New Jersey. ",
